    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Colonial hydrozoan that floats on the water surface and is frequently cast ashore following onshore winds. The colony members are bright blue and are supported by a flat, oval, transparent float marked by concentric grow rings and bearing a distinctive oval vertical ‘sail’ that sits obliquely across it. The colony members hang beneath the float and extend beyond its margins and include a single large central feeding individual and a large number of smaller individuals that bear short, simple tentacles for prey capture, or are reproductive.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_4720",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Colonies typically 30-40 mm across.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_4721",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Cosmopolitan in warm temperate seas.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Whole region, but rare on upper west coast.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_4722",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Floats on the ocean surface, where driven along at the mercy of prevailing winds blowing on the sails. There are both left and right-handed individuals, so these will be driven in different directions by the wind. The short feeding tentacles extend only about a centimetre below the float and are used to capture tiny planktonic organisms. The stinging cells thus possess very weak venom and are not harmful to humans, although allergic reactions have been reported, so it is still best not to handle live animals.</p><p>May be cast ashore in thousands after onshore winds, often along with other ‘blues’ including the related Blue buttons <i>Porpita porpita</i> and Bluebottles <i>Physalia physalis</i>, as well as predatory floating molluscs that feed on these species. Sometimes just the floats are found, the body having rotted away, and these are transparent, plastic-like and often thought to be man-made!</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_4723",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Feed on small particles and planktonic organisms in the surface water.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_4724",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>The familiar floating colony is the polyp phase of the life-cycle and each colony is either male or female. Reproductive individuals in the colony give rise to numerous tiny medusae (‘jellyfish’) each about 1 mm across, by a process of asexual budding. These reach sexual maturity in 2-3 weeks and in turn produce sperm and eggs which merge and develop into larvae that in turn give rise to new floating colonies.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_4725",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The oblique sail is very distinctive but is sometimes confused with the Blue Button <i>Porpita porpita,</i> which often washes up at the same time. However, that species has a circular, not oval, float and lacks any sail.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_4726",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town (p. 56).<br><br>Jones, G (2008). A Field Guide to the Marine Animals of the Cape Peninsula. SURG, Cape Town (p. 60).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_4727",
            "longText": null,
